<subSubSection id="C30A6528FFB4FF86C5931D21FDB6FD95" pageId="22" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BAF36A3FFB4FF86C5931D21FDB6FD95" blockId="22.[136,1089,334,528]" pageId="22" pageNumber="57">
Taxonomic notes. This species shows some simplification of the saccular processes with the reduction of the distal bundle of bristles on the left side. It means that the genital capsule secondarily seems to be more symmetrical than in other species of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D20FFB4FF86C4891DDCFDC0FE48" baseAuthorityName="Hufnagel" baseAuthorityYear="1766" box="[479,578,435,461]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mamestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nebulosa">
<emphasis id="B964EAB1FFB4FF86C4891DDCFDC0FE48" box="[479,578,435,461]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="57">nebulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group. It is widely distributed in the boreal and nemoral forest belts of North America and shows some clinal variation in colouration (
<bibRefCitation id="EF814B52FFB4FF86C4281D99FDAAFD95" author="MCCABE, T. M." box="[382,552,502,528]" pageId="22" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 141" refId="ref11622" refString="MCCABE, T. M. (1980): A reclassification of the Polia complex for North America (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae). - New York State Museum, Bulletin No. 432. i - vi, 1 - 141 pp." type="book chapter" year="1980">MCCABE 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
